Creating a smooth snake game with animations using images in C is a challenging task, as C is a low-level language that doesn't have built-in support for graphics or animations. However, I'll provide a high-level overview of how you can approach this task. We'll use the SDL (Simple DirectMedia Layer) library, which is a popular choice for creating games in C.

**Prerequisites:**

1. Install SDL library on your system. You can download it from the official website: <https://www.libsdl.org/download-2.0.php>
2. Familiarize yourself with the SDL API documentation: <https://wiki.libsdl.org/>

**Game Loop Structure:**

The game loop will be responsible for updating the game state and rendering the game screen. We'll use a loop that runs at a fixed framerate (e.g., 60 FPS).

```c
int main() {
    // Initialize SDL
    SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO);

    // Create a window and renderer
    SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Snake Game", SDL_WINDOWPOS_CENTERED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_CENTERED, 640, 480, SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN);
    SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);

    // Set up game variables
    bool running = true;
    SDL_Event event;
    Snake snake;
    Food food;

    // Game loop
    while (running) {
        // Handle events
        while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
            if (event.type == SDL_QUIT) {
                running = false;
            } else if (event.type == SDL_KEYDOWN) {
                handleKeys(&snake, event.key.keysym.sym);
            }
        }

        // Update game state
        updateGameState(&snake, &food);

        // Clear the renderer
        SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

        // Draw the game screen
        drawGameScreen(renderer, &snake, &food);

        // Update the renderer
        SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
    }

    // Clean up
    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    SDL_Quit();

    return 0;
}
```

**Rendering Images:**

To render images, you'll need to load them into memory using SDL's `IMG` library. You'll also need to create a `SDL_Surface` object to hold the image data and a `SDL_Texture` object to render the image on the screen.

```c
// Load the snake image
SDL_Surface* snakeImage = IMG_Load("snake.png");
SDL_Texture* snakeTexture = SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(renderer, snakeImage);

// Load the food image
SDL_Surface* foodImage = IMG_Load("food.png");
SDL_Texture* foodTexture = SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(renderer, foodImage);

// Draw the snake image
SDL_Rect snakeRect = { /* coordinates and dimensions */ };
SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, snakeTexture, NULL, &snakeRect);

// Draw the food image
SDL_Rect foodRect = { /* coordinates and dimensions */ };
SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, foodTexture, NULL, &foodRect);

// Release the image surfaces
SDL_FreeSurface(snakeImage);
SDL_FreeSurface(foodImage);

// Release the textures
SDL_DestroyTexture(snakeTexture);
SDL_DestroyTexture(foodTexture);
```

**Animation:**

To animate the snake movement, you'll need to update the snake's position and render it at the new position in the game loop. You can use SDL's `SDL_GetTicks()` function to keep track of time and animate the snake movement based on the elapsed time.

```c
// Update the snake position
int elapsedTime = SDL_GetTicks() - snake.lastMoveTicks;
snake.lastMoveTicks = SDL_GetTicks();
snake.x += snake.speed * (elapsedTime / 1000.0);
snake.y += snake.speed * (elapsedTime / 1000.0);

// Render the snake at the new position
snakeRect.x = snake.x;
snakeRect.y = snake.y;
SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, snakeTexture, NULL, &snakeRect);
```

This is a high-level overview of how you can approach creating a snake game with animations using images in C with SDL. You'll need to fill in the details and implement the game logic, collision detection, and scoring system.

Remember to consult the SDL API documentation and examples for more information on using the library and creating games with it. Good luck with your project!

